As main data sources we used :  ‚Ä¢ the DOAJ list (Directory of Open Access Journals)  [https://doaj.org/] ,   ‚Ä¢ the ROAD list (Directory of Open Access scholarly Resources) [http://road.issn.org/],   ‚Ä¢ PMC (PubMed Central)  [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/] ,   ‚Ä¢ CrossRef  [https://www.crossref.org/], and   ‚Ä¢ OpenAIRE  [https://www.openaire.eu/]   All these sources  fulfill the above mentioned requirements while other popular ‚Äòapparent‚Äô OA  sources such as ResearchGate and SciHub fail to meet  these two principle requirement s. Thus,  it is important to highlight here that our approach has a more policy and strategy perspective than a utilitarian one.

Recent developments such as ‚Äòoadoi‚Äô  (https://oadoi.org/ ), which is the source for  http://unpaywall.org , follow an approach very similar to the one presented here in order to  identify OA versions of publications.
